text: Vote for stuff and things
(retweets are nice too)

Games where too much land ramp happens feel meaningless to fight against. Because they have a resource that you can't counter. If I'm ramping with any other type you can, very easily, destroy them, since that doesn't happen with land ramp they can keep top decking haymakers.
MLD against ramp just means that the ramp deck ramps out again.
Instead, try [[Balancing Act]]!

attachments.fallback: Balancing Act {2}{W}{W} // Sorcery // Each player chooses a number of permanents they control equal to the number of permanents controlled by the player who controls the fewest, then sacrifices the rest. Each player discards cards the same way.
attachments.text:
Sorcery

attachments.title: Balancing Act {2}{W}{W}

text: Semi-wrath the board, cut the ramp player down to where everyone else is.
Game continues.
The thought process behind MLD against heavy ramp decks is they have fewer lands to find. There's a lower ceiling to their ramp now
Not to mention, with multi-color decks, sometimes ramp is more reliant on basics and if there's a lot on the field when MLD hits, well, now what do you search for?
If a ramp deck gets more than half the lands in their deck out and hasn't won...
MLD is not an answer to Ramp. It's a fine tool for aggro decks to keep up in higher levels of play, but honestly not good for anything else besides pissing off tables.
